Over two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between Government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the truce more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known rebel movement supported first by the White authorities of Rhodesia and then by the South African Government of the apartheid era in an effort to destabilize the country ' s independent Government.
After the truce in 1992, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to relapse into a full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and locals nervous.
The stakes are high for a rapidly growing economy, as the discovery of huge shelf reserves of gas and coal deposits in the north-west can attract more than $50 billion in investments over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy, and Anadarko from the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, the leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party have accused each other of the tensions that have arisen.
The Renamo Party claims that the Government was the instigator of the latest clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, the traditional fence of Renamo, on 17 October.
Attacks on former rebels then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the leader of the group, reported to the Financial Times by Fernando Mazanga, a representative of Renamo.
The government blames Renamo for initiating clashes, accusing the party of assaulting soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza tried to dispel fears of instability.
Hebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday, that Mr. Dhlakama felt like a “successful man” who wanted to use “all that was left of his power to try to prove that he could impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frellimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, fears increased following reports that Mazanga had declared Renamo ' s rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He informed the Financial Times that he had in mind the non-compliance with the agreement by the Frelimo party.
“Our goal is to return to the negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous negotiations between the parties have done little to ease the tension that has been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential men (Gebuza and Dhlakama) who ran into their foreheads,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert in Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and neither is willing to make the necessary concessions.
The Renamo Party, which is trying to achieve electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to obtain concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
Renamo’s vote has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Mozambican Democratic Movement (MDM), founded by former Renamo member, is expected to improve its performance in these elections.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Guebuza, who was due to resign next year, when his second term ended, wished to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn't want multiparty democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace, because he doesn't want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is not clear what capacity Renamo has, but it has already carried out destructive and rapid attacks on police stations and vehicles on a key motorway from north to south.
Most of the fighting took place in Sofala Province, which is several hundred kilometres north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies, including Rio Tinto and Vale, use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railways for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked whether Renamo would repeat the threat.
The Renamo Party wanted “to warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
Instability has increased government discontent, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and recent kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of an independent media company, Mediacoop.
