Here's the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With Eurocrisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
All over the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the euro to be abolished as a single currency are gaining power.
Even in Germany, the party of Euroskeptics “Alternative for Germany” — founded only this year — came out of nowhere and won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus effectively pushing the “Free Democrats” (the analogy of our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis was a turning point.
The austerity measures introduced by Berlin and the European Central Bank and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency led many to believe that the Europe project had gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are working with excessive fiscal deficits — that was only true of Greece.
In fact, the euro system has blocked its members at exchange rates that benefit German exporters — what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a predetermined disadvantage in terms of production opportunities compared to Germany.
The only means of saving is to cut wages and public spending, which Berlin actively supports.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is the deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacity.
As a result of the Green Energy package introduced by Brussels — a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the consumer’s expense — European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the US.
