Scientists have developed an anti - nicotine vaccine that could rob the smoking of pleasure cigarettes.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from life-long nicotine addiction.
Further tests are needed before human testing begins, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Whale Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that such a vaccine strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by testing all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome it with these modern means,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information for the production of anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a steady flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralize them before they reach the brain, prevent the smoker from getting nicotine.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine were "relaxed," and this is a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say,
These experiments are described in Science Transnational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
In order to maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be made so often that they proved expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibodies factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they wanted to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
