Indeed, demand in various parts of South-East Asia — where household debt is growing — is such that ValueMax, where it deals, became the third pawn shop in Singapore this week.
A mortgage on jewellery is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in the case of Ms. Amirthaling), but is almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawn shops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17%, slightly above the 15.4% offered at the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch at the same mall.
However, pawn shops have the advantage that they do not require credit testing or proof of salary and can lend faster than banks.
Millions of people throughout the region are therefore forced into pawn shops, as families feel pressure from higher costs of living and a rapid increase in household and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and low-cost loans fuelled by free monetary policies in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families resort to pawn shops to compensate for the decline in income as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, identified the increase in the family's credit shoulder, mainly due to the growth of the mortgage, as a risk factor for Asian banks' creditworthiness.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia led the list with 80 per cent of GDP, compared to 60 per cent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from the technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed a continuing decline in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“The point is that with rising prices, people in the middle and bottom [income scales] will look for ways to increase their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Wong, economist CIMB, Malaysian Bank.
Recordedly high gold prices in the past two years have increased the rush with which people lay their personal belongings because they use the opportunity to get money for their family decorations.
In Singapore, about 70 per cent of the items laid in 200 city-state plombards are gold.
People say, "The gold price looks good, let's put a gold chain on Grandma and get it back next month."
In Thailand, the largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen an increase in the number of clients using his offices in recent months, up to 20%.
