The company will finance the expansion using 60 per cent of the S$66 million this week as a result of the stock exchange in Singapore.
While some creditors had provoked criticism because of high interest rates, she said that the pawnboard not only offered cheaper tariffs than other creditors, it also did not increase debt directly.
“Clients plant items they already own, and the monetization of personal assets does not increase household debt”, she says.
