Mr. Hair said that he had presented his view to the New South Wales YMCA Board that the lesson for the organization in the Jonathan Lord incident was not “relating to the provision of information” by staff members, and the Board agreed with it.
Mr. Hair stated that the decision to force staff to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the charges were brought was taken by the YMCA Director General for Child Care, Liam Whitley.
He said that it was intended to prevent evidence from being corrupted, but it was “overtaken” and the decision was poorly implemented.
YMCA New South Wales was not a safe organization for children during Jonathan Lord's work in the period 2009-2011, and an expert on child abuse from the University of Griffith reported to the Commission.
