Scientists have shed light on the way the dog’s tail moves are connected to her mood.
Early studies have shown that satisfied dogs waving their tail to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while alarmed dogs waving their tail to the left.
But scientists now say that other members of the dog family can notice and respond to these subtle differences in tailings.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that people in the left and right sides of the brain have different roles in shaping drivers that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we've tried to look at it from other species.
He added that, like a human, dogs have the right side of the brain controlling the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotion.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the multiple tailings of other dogs, researchers observed animals watching movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analysed their behavior.
We'll probably soon find out why their tails sometimes go in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, "We showed dogs videos of dogs, either naturalistic versions or silhouette, to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or to the right."
When the animals saw that otherwise, the silent dog moved his tail to the right (from the point of view of the tail of the dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the tailing dog), their heartbeat increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs learned from their experience which movements they should worry about and which they should not.
He observes: “If there are a few encounters with other dogs and often one-way tails are associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience.”
Researchers say that these results can give owners, vets, and trainers a better understanding of the emotions of their animal.
An expert in dog behavior, John Bradshaw, an invited researcher at the University of Bristol veterinary school, said that this was not the first study to test whether the left and right side were relevant to the dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another research paper at Victoria University in Canada, he reported: “The dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was pointing to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming alarmed, the opposite of Italian research.”
He said that the difference could be because dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
“As there is sufficient evidence for various mammals that the two brain hemispheres are being used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception”, he said.
However, given the ease with which their conduct can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails are sometimes headed in one direction and sometimes in another.
