However, after the cardinal reached the age of 80, he was no longer able to take part in the pope’s election — the prerogative of the group of 120 “electoral cardinals”.
In reporting this news, the Vatican press secretary, Father Federico Lombardi, said that a meeting of all the present cardinals, known as the Consistory, would be held before the Sanctuary ceremony.
“Papa Francis decided to announce in advance his decision to convene a consistory in February in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings with cardinals from around the world”, said Lombardi.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said that by February, the number of election cardinals was likely to drop.
He said that the pope usually calls as many cardinals as it takes to bring the number of election cardinals back to 120, as well as the number of cardinals over the age of 80 as he wants.
The consistory next year will be important because it will be the first since Francis was elected last March, according to Valero.
So far, there is some kind of bias in favour of Europe, and especially for Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance”, he noted.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they are represented by a small number of cardinals.
It will also be the first chosen cardinals since Francis formed the Cardinal Council, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world who are mandated to seek ways to reform the church.
In the past, Dad made his own decision.
“Now Francis has selected eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said that it was “fully possible” that Francis would seek the cardinals’ advice.
But we've never been in this situation before — this is the first time we've ever had it.
Valero said that the popes usually appointed a cardinal bishop from large parishes, but Francis is “full of surprises, so we don't know who he's going to call.”
