Obama’s Voter’s Cry of Desperation
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing hope for change.
He says that Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to negate laudable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify problems with the Obama-reformed health system web site, drone attacks
The 2008 Obama campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what might be
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading an awfully sad book these days.
I thought this book would inspire me in a time of discouragement in my second year of medical school and restore a sense of hope to me.
It's called The Vigority for Victory, and it's a memoir about Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patients' reports at night and go to bed, this book brings me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people, and performances could be breathtaking.
The victory in the elections was impressive, and leading news programs paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates wept for joy, and my parents kept every newspaper they could find.
A young team of strategists was supposed to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
At the time of Obama's assumption of office in 2008, the level of support was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Return is now a brute awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It is hard to remember those days of optimism — they seem to be a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, changes have indeed occurred.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I commend Obama for his great and varied achievements, from the adoption of a law on affordable medical care to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the repeal of the rule of “Don't ask, don't talk,” the murder of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstruction has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, public health choices and the closure of Guantánamo Bay, among others.
But after countless times, when I stood on Obama’s side, defending it in front of colleagues and peers, I ran out of explanations that I could give.
I've reached a point of political despair.
The obstructionism of the Republicans cannot explain the authorization to tap foreign leaders or attack innocent children in other countries by drones.
He could not explain the collection of data on American privacy by the National Security Agency or the harassment of incriminators revealing government misconduct.
He cannot explain the murder of an American citizen, Anwar al-Awlaki, without trial or the failure to meet the limits of State funding and expenditure during the presidential campaign.
He cannot justify the findings of the report, which states that the efforts made by the White House to silence the media are “the most aggressive... since the Nixon administration.”
He has recently failed to justify the failure to develop a simple web site for more than three years after the law on affordable health care was signed.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have realized at the age of 18 that leadership might contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
Evidently, the election process is not a predictable programme of action, as our public dialogue will be shaped by an opposition political party and by such random events as the assassination in Newtown.
Nevertheless, all of the examples I have mentioned above show that they were to a large extent their own choice of administration.
And that's what's bothering me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and rude alternative, and seemed unable to make a decision on his own policies or views.
I thought that in his second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of future elections, would live up to the hopes we had heard for so long.
However, when Obama’s ratings fell below 45% this week, it became much more difficult to return to 2008 with the book.
It makes me long for many promises that have gone away.
This week, I read that part of the book that describes how Clinton defeated Obama in the primary elections in Pennsylvania.
At the meeting on the causes of failure, he told his staff that they must return to normal and remain faithful to their goal.
“I want us to return our appeal,” he said.
“We must remember who we are.”
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I agree with you.
The views expressed in the commentary belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
