RBS suspends two currency traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland suspended two traders in its foreign exchange unit, according to two people familiar with the situation, which is further evidence that global scrutiny by the regulators of alleged currency manipulation is rapidly gaining momentum.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators in investigations related to the world's largest financial market, with a daily turnover of $5.3 trillion.
These two traders will be the first RBS officers to be removed from the unfolding investigation, which coincides with the LIBOR inter-bank manipulation scandal.
By refusing to comment on the suspension, the bank confirmed that it had received requests for information from the regulatory authorities this month.
“Our ongoing investigation into this issue is ongoing, and we are fully cooperating with FCA and our other regulators,” reported the bank two weeks ago.
Last month, informed individuals said that RBS had transmitted e-mail and instant messages that had been received and sent by his former trader, the UK regulatory authority, the Financial Performance Control Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Asher, left RBS in 2010 and is known to have been granted leave for his current position as head of European spot trading in JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot tenders at Citi, took a vacation this week, while Matt Gardiner, a former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended from work by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders has been charged with any violations.
Mr. Asher's contact group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to persons informed.
The UBS bank reported this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finnma said that it was investigating alleged currency market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulators around the world — the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland’s competition authority, Weko, FCA, the U.S. Department of Justice, and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority — are considering allegations that bankers have conspired to influence the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also started internal checks or received requests for information from regulators, who are familiar with the situation.
Banks have been looking at instant messages and e-mails over several years in search of offences.
The verification news has sparked the activities of traders, which in recent years has been one of the largest sources of revenue for investment bank trading units, which this year, however, has encountered difficulties in view of the fact that weak currency volatility has reduced opportunities for buyers.
Some bankers have tried to reduce the seriousness of the situation by saying that a large and highly liquid currency market is almost impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say that this is not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily currency trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trade platforms and the wider use of domestic platforms by banks means that “you can begin to influence the market at a very low price.”
This news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired one of the traders of its stock trade division in the London Exchange this week after it had caused losses of almost $6 million at the end of last year.
The Bank immediately notified the relevant authorities and cooperated with its regulators.
“We are confident that the trader acted alone and that the issue has been localized,” Credit Suisse reported.
