In Egypt, the first freely elected President is sworn in
Mohammed Mursi is sworn in, but the day of its celebration is unlikely to mark the end of the political struggle in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Mohammed Mursi promised a “new Egypt” when he took the oath to become the first freely elected President of the country, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was overthrown 16 months ago.
At his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of State in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges in black robes in a courthouse on the shore of the Nile, built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We seek a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” said Morsi during a solemn ceremony broadcast live on State television.
“Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations for a new life — absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer with an American education from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that, for the most part of its 84 years of existence, was a banned organization that was targeted by successive governments.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and policemen when Mursi arrived with a small convoy shortly after 11:00 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the court building to welcome the new President, and unlike the presidential pump of Mubarak, the movement was stopped only for a short time to allow his convoy to pass on the normally lively road linking the city centre to the southern suburbs.
Although Morsi was ridiculed as a non-charismatic spare wheel of the Brothers, his personal prestige has increased dramatically since his victory and his Friday performance, in which he tried to present himself as a candidate not only for Islamists, but also for all those who want to complete the 2011 rebellion against authoritarian Mubarak.
“Today, Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” said Mursi, wearing a blue business suit with a red tie, to the judges in a wooden hall, where he took the oath.
Mursi later went to Cairo University, where he was to give his inaugural speech.
He received an official reception with an army orchestra that performed the national anthem, during which he stood at the stand “at ease”.
A military marshal, Hussein Tantavi, was present.
His arrival was met with the slogan “Army and the People One Hand”, which was chanted by hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Founded in 1908 as the mainstay of secular education, the University of Cairo became the wing of Islamist student groups in the 1970s.
Mursi took a symbolic oath on Friday at Tahrir Square, where a rebellion erupted that ended the authoritarian rule of Mubarak last year, and promised to regain the presidency, which was stripped of his office by a military council that took action from a deposed leader.
But by agreeing to take a formal oath of office before a court rather than before a parliament, as is customary, he does the will of the military, and this is a sign that the struggle for power will continue.
Mursi's speech at Tahrir Square was filled with theatrical populist gestures.
