The Rosbalt Agency has been stripped of media status for uncensored war.
On 31 October, Mosgorsud ruled that the registration licence of Rosbalt, written by Lenta, was invalid.
Roskomnadzor, for systematic and gross violations of the media law, insisted on the withdrawal of the agency ' s media status.
In the course of the trial, an unfortunate precedent was set: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"?
The “Rosbalt Information Agency” was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and operated as a federal information and analysis agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognized private Internet media in Russia.
However, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications has (and is still) drawn up notes referring to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the force structures continued throughout the Agency ' s existence.
While Rosbalt had a vast base of sources in various departments, it was also suggested that Natalia Chaplin, the wife of Victor Čerkezov, was the head of the project.
However, the role of Chaplina in the management of Rosbalt is not fully clear: it is commonly referred to as the “project leader”.
The director-general of the agency is Larissa Afonina, editor-in-chief, Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not been on federal media ratings, either by citation or by audience.
In October, the agency ranked 25th in the list of Russian media sites on LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the website rosebalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), and about three million unique visitors per month.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes of the Kremlin's powerlessness in its relations with Ukraine, the death of a soloist of the group "King and Cock", pogroms in the capital city of Birlev.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when the amendments to the media law came into force, which prohibited uncensorship of journalists.
The agency found a prohibited lexic in two videos published on the website ("Jigit of Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot Defiled Oil Towers").
Further parties describe in different ways.
Roskomnadzor, based on the videos found, accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the media law and requested the court to withdraw the licence from the agency.
In Rosbalt, it was argued that the agency's claims were unlawful: first, the rollers were not editorial materials, secondly, the words were disguised and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, they were removed from the site.
The agency appealed Roskomnadzor ' s claims to the Magistrate ' s Court, and when Mosgorsud accepted Roskomnadzor ' s claim on 22 October 2013, the complaints were still pending.
However, as early as 25, the justice of the peace had ruled against Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief, Nikolai Ulyanov, had been found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offences and had been fined 20,000 roubles, 10,000 for each commercial.
Obviously, that pre-empted the outcome of the Mosgorsuda hearing - if you abandon the idea that the outcome might have been prejudged earlier.
On 31 October, the court decided to invalidate Rosbalt's registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It is not possible to say that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The Agency supported the deputies of the State Duma (the declaration to the head of Roscomnadzor, Alexander Jarov, signed 26 deputies on 10 October; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the CPRF).
The Head of the Russian Union of Journalists, Allvolod Bogdanov, the President of the Moscow Union of Journalists, Pavel Gusev, and the President of the Presidential Council for Human Rights, Mikhail Fedotov, stated that the closure of the publication was unlawful.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, Roskomnadzor’s authorities even provided him with some assurance that the withdrawal of the licence would not be possible.
The Rosbalt trial showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer for the Russian media to be in Russia today is a big issue.
